 address:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>So dont make it seem like the show would not go on without you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
When I recruit folks for my groups, I automatically make me, my class, and my abilities the central focus of the group.  This way, the group will continue to go on regardless of who I might add or lose.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Now I have a slower, which is the core of a PoP group, and we started exping immediately while recruiting.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
In the groups that I have formed, a slower is useful but not a necessity, and certainly not the core.  It is a support role, although a very effective one.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>My lfg woes are mainly in PoV, and yes I do see just as many rogues and wizzies sitting around as well.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
In some cases, this is circumstantial.  In most cases, people are lfg and staying lfg because they are waiting for the right group makeup.  I have been turned down many times by folks lfg, but unwilling to duo with me, or group in anything but a Trinity group (Tank/cleric/slower).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Lower level players:<br>
1) Bring most of the abilities of their higher level companions.<br>
2) Are pleased to have a group in a higher level zone.<br>
3) Are easier to control and lead.<br>
4) Remember you well later.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well said, and something I take to heart.  Recruiting below your level has many advantages.  Recruiting at or above your level has its stumbling blocks.  It's exceedingly rare that I would be able to group up with a 65th level magician, but much more common to group up with 2 or 3 mid-50's.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The people who have the least problem finding groups in PoP are the people in the high level (*cough* *cough* *uber* *cough*) guilds, who also have the highest end gear and a metric butt ton of AA points.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Where did you get that information from?  I wouldn't call 44 AA's a metric butt ton.  My gear is average, or even a little below average.  I'm in a very nice guild, but I rarely depend on guild connections for my grouping needs.  The people who have the least problem finding groups in PoP are the ones who plan for it, train the AA's for it, and recruit/teach others.  Cousin Raz has the right idea.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you don't have epic, and can't get into groups in tier 1 zones, and can't solo in those zones without epic, how are you supposed to get parchments for 61 pets?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm still unepicced, yet I could have soloed in PoJ for parchments even at level 59 (which is when I first trained in Improved Reclaim).  Not a huge number of single pullable mobs, however.  That makes the camp much more doable with a partner.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
I agree that our soloing abilities do not exactly measure up to the prime solo classes, but lfg woes are frequently (though not always) a product of point of view and lack of improvisation. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ninjashimm>NinjaSHIMM</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 127<br> <font color=#333333>(1/31/03 4:31:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=438.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   .</span><hr size=1> <br>
